Statuses for particular messages (for example, sent, sending, not sent) and events that impact messages (for example, times when a connection stops or restarts).

"Message status history allows us to reconstruct the events that led to the app's current state, increasing the chances of understanding why a message-related issue happened and which component might be the culprit.
For example, through the message history we can tell:
• What happened to the messages sent and received before and after a specific problematic message.
• Whether there's a discrepancy between what is reported by the UI vs. what actually happened to the message, indicating a possible UI issue.
• The chronological order of events related to a message, and how far apart they were.
• The message state correlation among two or more messages (e.g. whether one stuck message is blocking another) and between messages and conversations."

"Issues related to sending and receiving messages are associated with bugs related to phone number normalization, including on the sender's side. Knowing the user's number allows the bug investigation to:
• Validate assumptions for how the number was formatted and normalized
• Disambiguate the user’s number from the receiver’s number
The user’s number is helpful to diagnose RCS registration and provisioning issues, because they can be used to look up the RCS provisioning and availability states of that user.
Phone numbers will be used by the engineering team for investigation purposes and will never be used to contact you or any of your recipients."
